y by allowing the driver to maintain focus on the road while interacting with the vehicle's systems. As the automotive sector moves towards autonomous driving, the integration of gesture recognition will be a key component in enabling natural, intuitive user interfaces.<p>Additionally, gesture recognition technology is being incorporated into advanced driver-assistance systems (ADAS) to monitor driver behavior and ensure safety. These systems use 3D gesture recognition to detect driver gestures and movements, such as hand signals or head gestures, to provide real-time feedback or issue warnings in critical situations. The continued development of autonomous vehicles and the rising adoption of smart technologies in the automotive sector are expected to further drive demand for gesture recognition systems, creating significant opportunities for growth in this application area.<h2>Others</h2><p>The "Others" category encompasses various additional applications of 2D and 3D gesture recognition systems, including healthcare, education, and retail sectors. In healthcare, gesture recognition is being utilized in rehabilitation settings, where patients use gestures to interact with therapeutic devices or monitor their progress. This technology also allows for remote patient monitoring, enabling healthcare professionals to assess a patient’s mobility or condition without physical contact. Furthermore, gesture recognition is also being explored for use in surgery, where surgeons could potentially use hand gestures to control robotic-assisted instruments, reducing the need for physical interaction and promoting greater precision.<p>In the retail sector, gesture recognition is being employed to create more immersive shopping experiences. Customers can interact with digital signage, virtual kiosks, or in-store displays by making hand movements or gestures. This technology allows retailers to enhance customer engagement, offering interactive features that enable a more personalize